review_blob: Bottle conditioned (500ml) - Note alcohol was 4.4 ABV (not sure if this is standard for the larger bottle, but definitely different than the 330mL in the photo. As I poured from a bottle I found it difficult to cultivate a proper head, particularly as I accidentally mixed some sediment from the bottle. Cloudy brownish gold with little to no memorable nose. Great mouthfeel with a full flavor of orange peel and lemon. Smooth finish and nice bitterness throughout. I hope they continue to brew but add some more active yeast that will better carbonate the bottle conditioned beers.

Draft - Nightengale (Clapham) - the UK version of Sierra Nevada with a little more bitterness. Great IPA with Elderflower and lemon tanginess. Finish is extra dry.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Tap - Railway Tavern - (Dalston) - very intense floral hop aroma, active mouthfeel ending with a breaking aroma of orange maltiness, finish is crisp with a coconut butterscotch ending.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Handpump Cask - Railway Tavern - Dalston - Big chocolate and coffee aromas from the beginning. Great active mouthfeel for a real ale - definitely not at all flat. Everything about this stout is fresh - the lasting coffee flavor must be accented by roasted malts with toffee finishes. Great beer to pair with Oysters, hamburgers, and steak.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask handpump - The Snooty Fox - (Newington Green)  - Reddish brown with a light bubbly head that disappears rather quickly. Radish and celery mouthfeel complimented by creamy oaky ness at the finish. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask hand pump - The Clarendon - (Newington Green) - Cloudy golden orange, elderflower hops, grapefruit dryness, strawberry middle sweatiness, full mouthfeel with a bit of lingering carbonation. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Gravity Cask - The Clarendon - (Newington Green) - so first to rate, surprised given that this beer won a 2010 cask festival in Wales. Strong citrus aroma of grapefruit and lemons, very little carbonation, bitter middle followed by long oaky finish. Golden yellow no head.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Gravity cask - The Clarendon - Newington Green - brown ale with hints of Kentish hops. Virtually no effervescence but perhaps due to the gravity pull. Finish is crisp with a dark mild sweet malty character. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask hand-pump - Evening Star - (Brighton) - pours golden yellow - unbelievable hippy aroma from start to finish. Flat lettuce, green onion middle, bitterness stays strong for several seconds. Would pair with a strong Brie cheese and crackers

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask hand-pump - Evening Star (Brighton) - reddish brown ale with traditional English disappearing head. Deep hop chapter from start to finish; lasting after feel with toffee throughout. Really excellent brew - would pair with lamb and smokey BBQ 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask hand pump - Evening Star (Brighton) - a great traditional English pale - bitter throughout, notes of Kentish hops and strong flavoring hops at the finish. Not much mouthfeel- but replaced with malty beginning.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask hand pump - Earth & Stars (Brighton) - awful. Might be a bad keg; apple cider finish that unfortunately taste like skunk. I might wrong though in which case - brown blond, clear, retained curtain head, lack of hop and malt character.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Draft - CoachHouse (Brighton) - a good refreshing beer on a warm afternoon. Golden yellow with only a small amount of effervescence. Only a small bit of character in the malts that seem to make the beer taste like a cider more than an a beer. Absolutely no mouthfeel, malt or perceptible hops.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Draft (not cask) - Coachhouse Brighton. Golden bitter, crisp orange peel start, frothy mouthfeel lasts well past the initial taste. Malty Eisboch smell that is very strong. Great beer, while disappointed not on cask, tastes great on a warm summer day from the lager pump.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask - Blacksmiths Arms (St Albans). - yellow orange-zest with malty sugar aftertaste. Orange peel middle, becomes more bitter over the taste horizon, short finish with a hoppy conclusion. Best with a BLT sandwich.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask - 5.3% - Blacksmiths Arms (St Albans). Brown ale - similar to Sam Adams - molasses and brown sugar with smoky bitterness. Not much to remember in the aftertaste. Good deal of alcohol for a cask ale - visible in the head retention.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask- Blacksmiths Arms (St Albans) - yellow pour ( looks like Coors Light) tastes much better. Lemon zest beginning, strawberry mash mellow mouth feel, very sweet finish. Great for a warm sunny afternoon.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask - The Goat (St. Albans)- disappointing beer given the emphasis on honey. Great orange colour, small traditional ale head - disappears rather quickly - almost total lack of anything from a smell perspective. Recommendation - add more honey, ferment another week - and serve a bit colder.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Bottle - dark pour, very little head. Aroma is not powerful, but there is an early chocolate sweetness that really makes the beer delicious.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

On tap (Seymour Inn - Jersey, Channel Islands). The smell of liberation is clearly defined by the citrus hops and Hellerathau malts. It is heavier ABV than comparable ales, but seems to finish with a very fresh after aroma. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Bottle- candy malts, low carbonation, dark bitter finish. Overwhelming sweet finish

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

On tap - Charles Dickens (Southwark) : brown/red brick color, Carmel start - citrus notes throughout, not much finish or lasting uniqueness.

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

On tap - Charles Lamb (Angel, Islington) - low carbonation, chocolate malt, sweeter than Guinness, finish not quite as bitter

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Bottle at Craft Beer Co (Chancery Lane, London) - well, let's start with the price 13.95 per bottle. I was expecting more hops, but the smell is great. Actually tastes like an Arrogant Bastard Light. 

---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad

Cask at Craft Beer Co. (Chancery Lane), great color, slightly more bitter than a traditional west coast Pale Ale. The citrus notes are very subtle and could actually be enhanced with more Kentish hops (or similar)


---Rated via Beer Buddy for iPad
